title: Mexican tourist town erupts into war as cartel clashes with army, foreigners warned to seek shelter
description: A Mexican resort town has descended into chaos as the cartel goes to war with the military over the death of a major leader.  On Sunday, drug cartels responded to the death of Jalisco New Generation leader Nemesio “El Mencho” Oseguera Cervantes in a military raid.  Several members of the narco gang went on a rampage on the streets in Puerto Vallarta, as tourists were warned to stay indoors.  The US State Department urged tourists to shelter in a safe place, as some have reported they are trapped in the region.  The cartel leader’s death followed a raid by Mexican forces in Jalisco on Sunday, with Mexican defence officials releasing a statement about the raid.  “During this operation, military personnel were attacked, so in defence of their integrity, they repelled the aggression, resulting in four members of the CJNG criminal group being killed at the scene and three seriously injured who lost their lives during their transfer by air to Mexico City,” the statement read.

title: ‘Extremely worried’: Eugenie and Beatrice to hold crisis talks with King following father’s arrest
description: GB News host Alex Armstrong discusses reports that Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor’s daughters Princess Eugenie and Princess Beatrice are set to hold “crisis talks” following their father’s arrest.  “They’ll be extremely worried that they’re getting dragged into this case, which inevitably they are,” he told Sky News host James Macpherson.  “All of the Yorks are engulfed in this in some way. It’s impossible for them to escape it.”

title: ‘Reckless’: ISIS brides returning to Australia under ‘Labor’s watch’
description: Opposition Leader Angus Taylor says Labor is failing to keep out “terrorist sympathisers” from Australia.  Mr Taylor said people who align with Islamic State are returning to Australia under “Labor’s watch”.  “This policy is reckless, it is dangerous, and it is exactly what I was talking about when I said upfront that we need to protect our way of life,” he said.

title: Australians left ‘gobsmacked’ by Labor’s ISIS bride scandal
description: Opposition Leader Angus Taylor says Australians are sitting at home “gobsmacked” with Labor’s inability to prevent ISIS brides returning.  Mr Taylor said Labor has done everything except “drive these people to the airport” to support them returning to Australia.  “Labor needs to be upfront with the Australian people about what is going on here.”

title: CNN confronts Gavin Newsom over California cost-of-living crisis
description: California Governor Gavin Newsom was confronted by CNN host Dana Bash on the cost of living in his state.  The CNN reporter grilled Gavin Newsom over California's high cost of sharing a story about a couple who left for Nashville.  Dana Bash said to the Governor, “California has the highest cost of living in the nation.”  “We were actually out to dinner here in Nashville last night… We met a couple from California.”  “They moved out of California because they couldn't afford the rent or even to buy a home, and also start a family.”  Governor Newsom gave an out-of-touch response about California’s achievements.  He countered back, “Yes, we have had hundreds of thousands of people move into California… The last two, three years, we have seen population growth.”  “We moved from sixth to the fourth-largest economy in the world, and we dominate now in every key industry from AI, quantum, robotics.”

title: ‘New peak level of humiliation’: Andrew ‘reduced to a meme’ after arrest
description: Sky News host Danica De Giorgio claims Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor has been “reduced to a meme” following his arrest earlier last week.  Mr Mountbatten-Windsor has been released under investigation on suspicion of misconduct in public office and has denied all allegations.  “It’s so diabolical, activists have hung up a photo of him leaving the police station after his arrest at the Louvre in Paris with the caption, ‘He’s Sweating Now – 2026’, placed just below it,” Ms De Giorgio said.  “It’s an absolute new peak level of humiliation because Andrew has become a total parody of himself.”

title: Donald Trump congratulates USA men's hockey team following crushing victory over Canada
description: US President Donald Trump has congratulated the USA men’s hockey team following their 2-1 victory over rivals Canada.  Team USA’s victory over Canada, which helped them secure Olympic gold, was their first since 1980.  Coach Mike Sullivan spoke about Trump’s call with the team, revealing the president told the team he was “proud” of them.  “He just spoke to the group, expressing how proud he was of the group and congratulating everybody on the win. Obviously, this game in a lot of ways was an inspiration to our country,” Coach Sullivan said.  “I can’t tell you how many texts I’ve received over the last day or so about watch parties at 8 in the morning. I think from a viewership standpoint in the United States, there were a lot of people paying attention, the president included.”

title: Donald Trump announces global tariff increases as ‘instant reaction’ to Supreme Court loss
description: Bondi Partners Senior Advisor Peter McGauran says US President Donald Trump’s new global tariffs are an “instant reaction” to the Supreme Court ruling on tariffs.  US President Donald Trump announces 15 per cent tariffs globally after the Supreme Court loss.  Mr McGauren said the Australian government must “stay calm” until the “dust settles”.

title: AOC breaks silence with desperate meltdown after humiliating word salads in Munich
description: AOC has broken her silence following that humiliating performance at the Munich Security Conference.  The Democrat took to her Instagram account to clear the air about her stumbles and mumbles during the conference last week. But instead of explaining why she didn’t know basic geography, history or current international politics, she doubled down and justified her word salad answers.

title: Left blasted for 'normalising' political violence after Secret Service kills armed man at Mar-a-Lago
description: US Treasury Secretary has called out the “venom” infiltrating the left following an armed man being killed by the Secret Service after breaching the security perimeter at Mar-a-Lago.  The man was reportedly carrying a shotgun and fuel when he was stopped and killed by members of the Secret Service. The incident occurred at 1:30 am local time on Sunday morning.  At the time of the incident, US President Donald Trump was in Washington and not at his Florida residence.  The shooting marks the third time the president has targeted by political violence, with another incident taking place at Mar-a-Lago, as well as the infamous assassination in Butler, Pennsylvania.  The Treasury secretary finished his remark by stating the “venom from the left” is an “existential threat”.

title: Removing Andrew from the royal line of succession would be ‘hugely complicated’
description: Former UK attorney general Sir Michael Ellis explains the complexities of removing Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor from the royal succession line.  “It would be hugely complicated, hugely expensive, it would take probably two or three years,” he told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  Sir Ellis’ remarks come amid calls for the former Duke of York to be removed from the royal line of succession after revelations came to light about his ties to Jeffrey Epstein.  Those calls have been amplified after Mr Mountbatten-Windsor’s arrest earlier last week and subsequent release under investigation on suspicion of misconduct in public office.  Mr Mountbatten-Windsor has denied all allegations.

title: Andrew faces the potential of ‘life imprisonment’ if found guilty following arrest
description: Former UK attorney general Sir Michael Ellis discusses the investigation into Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor on suspicion of misconduct in public office.  The former Duke of York was arrested earlier last week following revelations from the Epstein files of his time as the UK’s trade envoy, but was later released and now faces an investigation.  Mr Mountbatten-Windsor has denied any wrongdoing.  “The offence is an imprisonable offence. It carries actually what’s known as an at-large sentence,” Sir Ellis told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “Parliament ... never set a maximum penalty so the maximum penalty is life imprisonment.”

title: Public support for the Royal Family takes a dive amid messy Andrew-Epstein scandal
description: Sky News host Danica De Giorgio analyses the polls which reveal a drop in support for members of the Royal Family amid the fallout over Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor’s arrest and ties to Jeffrey Epstein.  “Public support for the Royal Family has fallen seven per cent in four months because of this Andrew scandal,” she said.  “Every single member has had a downturn.”

title: Andrew hit with damning new Epstein claims as saga continues to spiral out of control
description: Former UK attorney general Sir Michael Ellis discusses former UK prime minister Gordon Brown’s claim that Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor may have used taxpayer-funded jets and RAF bases to meet with Jeffrey Epstein.  “I think we need to be very careful at the moment because obviously we have to bear in mind that the presumption of innocence applies,” he told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  This comes after Mr Mountbatten-Windsor was arrested but later released under investigation on suspicion of misconduct in public office.  The former Duke of York has denied any wrongdoing in relation to Epstein.

title: Donald Trump says ‘cartels are running Mexico' and warns action may be coming
description: US President Donald Trump has sensationally declared that “the cartels are running Mexico.”  During a call-in to Fox & Friends, Trump claimed Mexican President Claudia Sheinbaum has effectively ceded control of the country to drug cartels.  “The cartels are running Mexico. She’s not running Mexico — the cartels are running Mexico,” Trump said.  “Something is going to have to be done with Mexico.”  He claimed Sheinbaum is “very frightened of the cartels,” suggesting that fear has prevented more action against drug trafficking groups.  The Trump administration continues to target cartel violence and fentanyl trafficking as urgent national security threats.
